<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="159" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,836,2015]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,215]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="159" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1772,1799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito, 2019" authorityName="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito" authorityYear="2019" box="[342,569,1772,1798]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcifera" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[342,569,1772,1798]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Ophiomyia falcifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[576,666,1773,1799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[576,666,1773,1799]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is quite similar to other species of this genus without a vibrissal fascicus and a slightly evident facial keel, similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meigen)" authorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[706,958,1808,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulicaria">
<emphasis box="[706,844,1808,1835]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">O. pulicaria</emphasis>
(Meigen)
</taxonomicName>
. Usually, 
<taxonomicName box="[1068,1192,1808,1834]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1068,1192,1808,1834]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have a strong facial keel accompanied by a medial bulb, but many have only a slightly evident keel without the bulb. As in other 
<taxonomicName box="[151,275,1880,1906]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,275,1880,1906]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the clypeus is truncated and the aedeagus is asymmetric (
<bibRefCitation author="Lonsdale, O." box="[933,1105,1880,1907]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" pagination="481 - 513" refId="ref19446" refString="Lonsdale, O. (2014) Redefinition and synonymy of genera in the Ophiomyia genus group, with the description of Euhexomyza new genus (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 146 (5), 481 - 513. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / tce. 2014.2" type="journal article" year="2014">Lonsdale 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The lunule in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito" authorityYear="2019" box="[1281,1410,1880,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcifera">
<emphasis box="[1281,1410,1880,1907]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">O. falcifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly bent inward, similar to some other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[766,890,1916,1942]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[766,890,1916,1942]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the ocellar triangle is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Deeming)" authorityName="Deeming" baseAuthorityName="Deeming" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arabica">
<emphasis box="[1313,1436,1916,1943]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">O. arabica</emphasis>
(Deeming)
</taxonomicName>
. The unique shape of the distiphallus is essential to differentiate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito" authorityYear="2019" box="[1010,1140,1952,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcifera">
<emphasis box="[1010,1140,1952,1979]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">O. falcifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other species of this genus. The polyphagous species 
<emphasis box="[523,771,1988,2014]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Topicomyia polyphyta</emphasis>
(Kleinschmidt) is the only agromyzid previously recorded from host-plants of the family 
<taxonomicName authority="(Benavent-Corai et al. 2005)" authorityName="Benavent-Corai" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Benavent-Corai" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[494,941,152,179]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
Meliaceae (
<bibRefCitation author="Benavent-Corai, J. &amp; Martinez, M. &amp; Jimenez Peydro, R." box="[623,933,152,179]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref18038" refString="Benavent-Corai, J. Martinez, M. &amp; Jimenez Peydro, R. (2005) Catalogue of the host plants of the world Agromyzidae (Diptera). Bollettino di Zoologica Agraria e di Bachicoltura, Series II, 37, 1 - 97." type="journal article" year="2005">
Benavent-Corai 
<emphasis box="[809,866,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">et al.</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monteiro &amp; Barbosa &amp; Esposito" authorityYear="2019" box="[1066,1196,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falcifera">
<emphasis box="[1066,1196,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">O. falcifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[1202,1328,153,179]" form="linear" pageId="8" pageNumber="159" rank="form">form linear</taxonomicName>
mines on leaf surface. Pupation takes place inside mines.
</paragraph>
